================================
TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS
================================

1. Preserve existing stack
- Detect the actual framework and routing approach in the repository.
- If the repo already uses React Router, Next.js App Router, Next.js Pages Router, or another router, adapt the shell to that existing pattern.
- Do not migrate frameworks.
- Do not introduce a second routing system.

2. Preserve existing styling approach
- If the repo already uses Tailwind, CSS modules, SCSS, styled-components, or another styling approach, keep that approach.
- Use low-complexity shell styling only.
- Focus on spacing, hierarchy, layout, and placeholders, not final UI finish.

3. Preserve existing navigation architecture
- If navigation is config-driven, extend config.
- If navigation is component-driven, extend component structure.
- Do not hardcode duplicate route definitions in multiple places unnecessarily.

4. Create placeholder pages safely
Each placeholder page should:
- use the correct shell
- include a clear route title
- include a short section label
- include a “shell placeholder” note
- visually confirm that route wiring works
- be easy to replace later with real content

5. Keep logic out
Do not implement:
- submission handlers
- calculators
- affiliate redirects
- auth flows beyond shell-level page structure
- billing workflows
- Firestore hooks
- API calls
- CMS queries

6. Keep code organized
Prefer:
- shared layout components
- route-group or section directories
- clearly named placeholder page components
- reusable shell wrappers

7. Minimize risk
- avoid changing unrelated business logic
- avoid renaming stable existing routes unless absolutely necessary
- if an existing route conflicts, preserve compatibility and note it clearly
- do not delete existing working pages unless replacing them in a safe, route-compatible way

